'''''Fox & Friends''''' is an [[United States|American]] early-morning news and opinion talk show that begins at 6:00 a.m. [[North American Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Time]] with the latest ''[[Fox News Live]]'' headlines and news of the morning. It continues with a variety of segments including breaking news, interviews, updates of news stories with correspondents, and entertainment segments. 

== History ==
''Fox & Friends'' evolved from ''Fox X-press'', Fox News Channel's original morning news program.

After the [[September 11, 2001 attacks|September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks]], an additional hour was added to the beginning of the weekday show, but branded as a separate show called ''Fox & Friends First''. It was the first Fox News show to air live for the day, starting at 6:00 a.m. It was discontinued on July 13, 2008 and replaced with an additional hour of ''Fox & Friends''<ref>[http://www.mediabistro.com/tvnewser/changes-at-fox-friends_b20086 Changes at Fox & Friends], ''TVNewser'', July 14, 2008.</ref> The ''[[Fox & Friends First]]'' title was later reintroduced on March 5, 2012, also as a separate show airing one hour before the main three-hour program, but using a separate slate of rotating anchors.<ref>[http://www.mediabistro.com/tvnewser/fox-friends-first-goes-on-the-air_b114985 ‘Fox & Friends First’ Goes on the Air], ''TVNewser'', March 5, 2012.</ref> After the show has ended for the day, a short online-only web show named ''After The Show Show'' which features behind-the-scenes footage not shown on air, is streamed on the Fox News website. It lasts from less than 3 minutes to 10 minutes.

== Ratings ==
Since the arrival of Elizabeth Hasselbeck in September 2013, the show climbed 23 percent in total viewers compared to its average for the third quarter of 2013, and 22 percent in the key 25-54 news demo.  For Hasselbeck’s first four weeks on the show, “Fox & Friends” averaged 1.226 million total viewers, up from the 1.058 that the show averaged for the third quarter of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewrap.com/fox-friends-gets-double-digit-ratings-boost-elisabeth-hasselbeck/ |title=Fox and Friends' with Elizabeth Hasselbeck  –  |publisher=THE WRAP Covering Hollywood |date=October 15, 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/10/fncs-fox-friends-jumps-22-with-elisabeth-hasselbeck/ |title=Fox and Friends jump 22% with Elizabeth Hasselbeck  –  |publisher=Deadline Hollywood |date=October 15, 2014 |accessdate=2014-02-17}}</ref>
In comparison, morning shows from both [[CNN]] and [[msnbc]] combined to average 792,000 viewers.  The show has seen a slight drop in early 2014 but still has managed to draw over 10 million viewers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/02/14/cable-news-ratings-for-thursday-february-13-2014/237080/ |title=Cable News Ratings - publisher=TV by the Numbers |date=February 13, 2014 |accessdate=2014-02-18}}</ref>

== Political stance ==
''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that ''Fox & Friends'' "has become a powerful platform for some of the most strident attacks on President Obama."<ref name="nyt">{{cite news | work = [[New York Times]] | title = Enemies and Allies for 'Friends' | url = http://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/21/arts/television/fox-friends-finds-ratings-and-controversy.html | first=  Jeremy | last = Peters | accessdate = June 22, 2012 | date = June 20, 2012}}</ref> The program has provided a platform for [[Barack Obama religion conspiracy theories|conspiracy theories about Obama's religion]] and, in May 2012, aired a 4-minute video attacking Obama's record as President.<ref name="nyt"/> The video was widely criticized as a political attack ad masquerading as journalism,<ref name="nyt-video">{{cite news | work = [[New York Times]] | url = http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/30/obama-video-on-fox-news-criticized-as-attack-ad/ | date = May 30, 2012 | first= Brian | last = Stelter | title = Obama Video on Fox News Criticized as Attack Ad | accessdate = June 22, 2012}}</ref><ref name="sun">{{cite news | work= [[Baltimore Sun]] | url = http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/tv/z-on-tv-blog/bal-romney-fox-news-obama-attack-ad-20120530,0,2738139.story | title = With Romney now official, Fox News gets shamelessly political | first = David | last = Zurawik | date = May 30, 2012 | accessdate = June 22, 2012}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]'' television critic [[James Poniewozik]] wrote: "It’s hard to imagine a more over-the-top parody of Fox raw-meat-hurling, fear-stoking, base-pleasing agitprop."<ref name="time">{{Cite news | work = [[Time (magazine)|TIME]] | first= James | last = Poniewozik | accessdate = June 22, 2012 | date = May 31, 2012 | title = Fox News Produces Greatest Fox News Parody Video Ever | url = http://entertainment.time.com/2012/05/31/fox-news-produces-greatest-fox-news-parody-video-ever/ | authorlink = James Poniewozik}}</ref>

In response, a Fox News exec vice-president 'disavowed' the video, blaming an associate producer and that the video 'slipped by' senior managers at the network.<ref name="bw">{{cite news | agency  = Associated Press | work = [[BusinessWeek]] | title = Controversial Fox News video: personnel hardball? | first = David | last = Bauder | url = http://www.businessweek.com/ap/2012-06/D9V6D2900.htm | date = June 4, 2012 | accessdate = June 22, 2012}}</ref> Fox stated that the show was entertainment and "does not pretend to be straight news."<ref name="nyt"/> Citing anonymous sources, the ''New York Times'' reported that some reporters, producers and executives at Fox were 'embarrassed' by the show, which remains by far the highest-rated cable show in its time slot as of June 2012.<ref name="nyt"/>

On October 5, 2013, while covering the government shutdown which had led to the closing of a veteran's museum, presenter Kooiman claimed that President Obama had offered "to pay out of his own pocket for the museum of Muslim culture". The story seemed to have been sourced from a spoof news website [[National Report]], and the following week an on-air apology was made for "reporting a story based on poor research that was not true".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaite.com/tv/fox-friends-host-anna-kooiman-apologizes-for-airing-phony-muslim-museum-story/|title=Fox & Friends Host Anna Kooiman Apologizes for Airing Phony Muslim Museum Story|date=14 October 2013|work=mediaite.com|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref>

